AMENDMENTS TO LB596
Introduced by Government, Military and Veterans Affairs.
1 1. Strike the original sections and insert the following new
2 sections:
3 Section 1. Section 23-346.01, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska,
4 is amended to read:
5 23-346.01 In It shall be the duty of the county clerk, in all
6 counties having a population of one hundred fifty thousand or more
7 inhabitants as determined by the most recent federal decennial census, on
8 or before December 1, annually, to prepare separate estimates of the
9 supplies, materials, equipment and machinery required for the use of the
10 county officers during the coming year, which by law are not required to
11 be furnished by the state, and, in order to properly estimate the amounts
12 of supplies, materials, equipment and machinery to be needed by the
13 county government, the county clerk or the county clerk's designee shall
14 keep a perpetual inventory of all personal property of the county.
15 Sec. 2. Section 23-1303, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
16 amended to read:
17 23-1303 (1) The county clerk shall not issue any county warrants
18 except upon claims approved by the county board. Every warrant issued
19 shall be numbered consecutively as allowed from July 1 to June 30,
20 corresponding with the fiscal year of the county. The county clerk shall
21 maintain records including the date, amount, and number of each warrant,
22 the name of the person to whom a warrant is issued, and the date a
23 warrant is returned as canceled. The records shall be made accessible to
24 the public for viewing, in either an electronic or printed format.
25 (2)(a) The county clerk shall develop and implement a system of
26 warrant preparation and issuance by electronic or mechanical means which
27 is compatible with the funds transfer system established by the county
-1-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 treasurer pursuant to subsection (6) of this section. The county clerk
2 may combine warrants for individual funds into a summary warrant that
3 lists each fund and the amount requested from such fund.
4 (b) Warrant includes an order issued by the chairperson of the
5 county board and countersigned by the county clerk directing that the
6 county treasurer make payment in a specified amount to a specified payee
7 by the use of a dual signature negotiable instrument as provided for in
8 subsections (3) and (4) of this section, an electronic funds transfer
9 system, a telephonic funds transfer system, funds transfers as provided
10 in article 4A, Uniform Commercial Code, a mechanical funds transfer
11 system, or any other funds transfer system established by the county
12 treasurer.
13 (3) The chairperson of the county board shall sign each warrant or
14 shall cause each warrant to be signed in his or her behalf either
15 personally, by delegation of authority, or by facsimile or electronic
16 signature. The signature of the chairperson of the county board shall
17 signify that the payment intended by a warrant bearing such signature is
18 proper under the appropriate laws of the state and resolutions of the
19 county.
20 (4) The county clerk shall countersign all warrants issued by the
21 chairperson of the county board either personally, by delegation of
22 authority, or by facsimile or electronic signature.
23 (5) The county treasurer shall, if requested by the county clerk or
24 the county board, establish procedures and processes for facsimile or
25 electronic signature of warrants.
26 (6) The county treasurer may establish and operate an electronic
27 funds transfer system, a telephonic funds transfer system, funds
28 transfers as provided for in article 4A, Uniform Commercial Code, a
29 mechanical funds transfer system, or any other funds transfer system for
30 the payment of funds from and the deposit of receipts into the county
31 treasury. Such system as established by the county treasurer shall employ
-2-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 internal control safeguards and after meeting such safeguards shall be
2 deemed to satisfy any signature requirements. The use of an electronic
3 funds transfer system, a telephonic funds transfer system, funds
4 transfers as provided for in article 4A, Uniform Commercial Code, a
5 mechanical funds transfer system, or any other funds transfer system
6 established by the county treasurer shall not create any rights that
7 would not have been created had an order, drawn by the chairperson of the
8 county board upon the county treasurer directing the latter to pay a
9 specified amount to a specified payee by the use of a dual signature
10 negotiable instrument as provided for in subsections (3) and (4) of this
11 section, been used as the payment medium.
12 Sec. 3. Section 23-1309, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
13 amended to read:
14 23-1309 (1) It shall be the duty of the county clerk in each county
15 to keep in a separate book or books, entitled Discharge Record, a copy of
16 all discharges or records of separation from active duty from the armed
17 forces of the United States. Information contained in the Discharge
18 Record shall be confidential and made available only to the veteran,
19 county veterans service officer, or post service officer of a recognized
20 veterans organization.
21 (2) The county clerk may transfer the Discharge Record to the State
22 Archives of the Nebraska State Historical Society for permanent
23 preservation after the veteran's federal Official Military Personnel File
24 becomes a public archival record or after sixty-two years, whichever is
25 later.
26 Sec. 4. Section 23-1517.01, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
27 amended to read:
28 23-1517.01 (1) The recording of all instruments by the roll form of
29 microfilm or other accessible durable medium may be substituted for the
30 method of recording instruments in books, and the filing of all documents
31 by the roll form of microfilm or other accessible durable medium may be
-3-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 substituted for the method of filing original documents. If this method
2 of recording instruments on microfilm or filing documents on microfilm is
3 used, the original instruments so recorded and the original documents so
4 filed need not be retained after the microfilm or other accessible
5 durable medium has been verified for accuracy and quality, and a security
6 copy shall on silver negative microfilm in roll form must be maintained
7 and filed off premises under safe conditions to insure the protection of
8 the records and shall meet the microfilm standards as prescribed by the
9 State Records Administrator as provided in sections 84-1201 to 84-1220.
10 The fee books shall provide the proper index information as to the
11 microfilm roll and numerical sequence of all such recorded instruments
12 and of all such filed documents. The internal reference copies or work
13 copies of the instruments recorded on microfilm and of documents filed on
14 microfilm may be in any photographic form to provide the necessary
15 information as may be determined by the official in charge.
16 (2) For purposes of this section, a medium is accessible if it is
17 able to be retrieved through intellectual, digital, or physical means
18 within institutional or legal parameters.
19 Sec. 5. Section 23-1527, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
20 amended to read:
21 23-1527 A certified copy of a petition, with schedules omitted,
22 commencing a proceeding under the laws of the United States relating to
23 bankruptcy or a certified copy of the decree of adjudication or a
24 certified copy of an order approving the bond of the trustee appointed in
25 such proceedings shall be filed, indexed, and recorded in the office of
26 the register of deeds of the county in which is located real property in
27 which the bankrupt has an interest in the same manner as federal liens
28 are filed, indexed, and recorded pursuant to the Uniform Federal Lien
29 Registration Act. The filing fee for such recording shall be the same as
30 the fee for filing and recording as set forth in section 9-525, Uniform
31 Commercial Code. The register of deeds shall file the notices in a file
-4-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 kept for such purpose and designated Notice of Bankruptcy Proceedings,
2 except that in offices filing by the roll form of microfilm or other
3 accessible durable medium pursuant to section 23-1517.01, the original
4 notices need not be retained.
5 Sec. 6. Section 25-523, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
6 amended to read:
7 25-523 (1) For purposes of this section:
8 (a) Digital newspaper means an Internet website that:
9 (i) Employs staff in the county from which the digital newspaper is
10 published online;
11 (ii) Has at least three hundred paid subscribers if located in a
12 city of the metropolitan class or city of the primary class;
13 (iii) Has at least two hundred paid subscribers if located in a city
14 of the first class, city of the second class, or village;
15 (iv) Publishes exclusively online;
16 (v) Has updated its news at least once each week for at least one
17 year prior to the publication of a notice; and
18 (vi) Reports on events and governmental activities of local
19 interest; and
20 (b) E-edition means a digital facsimile of a newspaper's print
21 edition that is accessible from such newspaper's website and is
22 substantially the same in both format and content as the print edition of
23 such newspaper.
24 (2)(a) No newspaper shall be considered a legal newspaper for the
25 publication of legal and other official notices unless the same shall
26 have a bona fide circulation of at least three hundred paid subscriptions
27 if located in a city of the metropolitan class or a city of the primary
28 class or at least two hundred paid subscriptions if located in a city of
29 the first class, city of the second class, or village weekly, and shall
30 have been published within the county or an adjacent county for fifty-two
31 successive weeks prior to the publication of such notice, and then
-5-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 subsequently at least fifty times per year. and be printed, either in
2 whole or in part, in an office maintained at the place of publication;
3 Provided, that
4 (b) The e-edition of a legal newspaper shall be considered a legal
5 newspaper for the publication of legal and other official notices only if
6 (i) such notices are contemporaneously published in the print edition of
7 such newspaper or (ii) the newspaper (A) has ceased publication of its
8 print edition and (B) was considered a legal newspaper when it ceased
9 publication.
10 (c) If no newspaper considered to be a legal newspaper publishes
11 either a print edition or an e-edition within a county, any legal and
12 other official notices directed to persons or entities in that county may
13 be published in a digital newspaper within the county if available at a
14 rate not to exceed legal notice rates pursuant to sections 33-141 to
15 33-143.
16 (3) Nothing nothing in this section shall invalidate the publication
17 in a newspaper which has suspended publication or been printed outside of
18 the county, on account of fire, flood, or other unavoidable accident, for
19 not to exceed ten weeks, in the year last preceding the first publication
20 of a legal notice, advertising, or publication. All ; provided further,
21 that all publications made prior to May 22, 1941, in a newspaper which
22 has, on account of flood, fire, or other unavoidable accident, suspended
23 publication or been printed in an office outside of the county, are
24 hereby legalized ; provided further, that all newspapers, otherwise
25 complying herewith, which have, on account of flood, fire or other
26 unavoidable accident, suspended publication or been printed in an office
27 outside of the county, for not to exceed ten weeks in any year, are
28 hereby legalized; and provided further, that the publication of legal or
29 other official notices in the English language in foreign language
30 newspapers published within the county for fifty-two successive weeks
31 prior to the publication of such a notice, and printed either in whole or
-6-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 in part in an office maintained at the place of publication, shall also
2 be legal.
3 Sec. 7. Section 25-2228, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
4 2024, is amended to read:
5 25-2228 (1) All legal publications and notices of whatever kind or
6 character that may by law be required to be published a certain number of
7 days or a certain number of weeks shall be legally published when they
8 have been published in a print edition of one issue in each week in a
9 daily, weekly, semiweekly, or triweekly newspaper, or in an e-edition or
10 digital newspaper as provided in section 25-523 such publication in such
11 daily, semiweekly, or triweekly paper or papers to be made upon any one
12 day of the week upon which such paper is published. Nothing in this
13 section shall be construed as preventing the publication of such legal
14 notices and publications in weekly newspapers. Any newspaper publishing
15 such legal notices or publications as provided in this section must shall
16 be otherwise qualified under section 25-523 existing law to publish such
17 notices or publications. All legal publications and all notices of
18 whatever kind or character that may be required by law to be published a
19 certain number of days or a certain number of weeks, shall be and hereby
20 are declared to be legally published when they shall have been published
21 once a week in a weekly, semiweekly, triweekly, or daily newspaper for
22 the number of weeks, covering the period of publication. For the purpose
23 of this section, when a newspaper is published regularly four or more
24 times each week, it shall be deemed a daily newspaper.
25 (2) Beginning October 1, 2022, all legal publications and notices of
26 whatever kind or character that may by law be required to be published a
27 certain number of days or a certain number of weeks shall also be posted
28 by the newspaper or digital newspaper publishing such legal publications
29 or notices on a statewide website established and maintained as a
30 repository for such notices by a majority of Nebraska newspapers. A
31 website posting or a failure to make such website posting under this
-7-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 subsection shall not affect the validity of the publication or notice
2 published under subsection (1) of this section.
3 Sec. 8. Section 33-110, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
4 amended to read:
5 33-110 County clerks shall receive no fee for the performance of the
6 following services: For issuing certificates of election; for performing
7 the duties of clerk of the county board; for taking acknowledgments of
8 claims against the county; for attesting or certifying any document
9 authorized by the county board or required by the departments of the
10 state; or for recording Army or Navy discharges or furnishing certified
11 copies thereof to be used in connection with any claim for compensation
12 or disability. A charge of twenty-five cents shall be made for any other
13 certificate and seal unless otherwise provided. The fees collected shall
14 be credited to the county general fund.
15 County clerks shall receive a fee of fifty twenty-five dollars for
16 the entire proceedings of issuing a marriage license, administering the
17 related oaths or affirmations, and recording a marriage certificate. An
18 additional fee of sixteen nine dollars shall be made for each certified
19 copy of a marriage record on file in the office of the county clerk. Both
20 such fees shall be deposited in the county general fund.
