29 Sec. 13. Section 84-1412, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
30 amended to read:
31 84-1412 (1) Subject to the Open Meetings Act, the public has the
-33-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 right to attend and the right to speak at meetings of public bodies, and
2 all or any part of a meeting of a public body, except for closed sessions
3 called pursuant to section 84-1410, may be videotaped, televised,
4 photographed, broadcast, or recorded by any person in attendance by means
5 of a tape recorder, a camera, video equipment, or any other means of
6 pictorial or sonic reproduction or in writing. Except for closed sessions
7 called pursuant to section 84-1410, a public body shall allow members of
8 the public an opportunity to speak at each meeting.
9 (2) It shall not be a violation of subsection (1) of this section
10 for any public body to make and enforce reasonable rules and regulations
11 regarding the conduct of persons attending, speaking at, videotaping,
12 televising, photographing, broadcasting, or recording its meetings,
13 including meetings held by virtual conferencing.
14 (3) No public body shall require members of the public to identify
15 themselves as a condition for admission to the meeting nor shall such
16 body require that the name of any member of the public be placed on the
17 agenda prior to such meeting in order to speak about items on the agenda.
18 The body shall require any member of the public desiring to address the
19 body to identify himself or herself, including an address and the name of
20 any organization represented by such person unless the address
21 requirement is waived to protect the security of the individual.
22 (4) No public body shall, for the purpose of circumventing the Open
23 Meetings Act, hold a meeting in a place known by the body to be too small
24 to accommodate the anticipated audience.
25 (5) No public body shall be deemed in violation of this section if
26 it holds its meeting in its traditional meeting place which is located in
27 this state.
28 (6) No public body shall be deemed in violation of this section if
29 it holds a meeting outside of this state if, but only if:
30 (a) A member entity of the public body is located outside of this
31 state and the meeting is in that member's jurisdiction;
-34-

AM2282 AM2282
LB596 LB596
LPB - 02/25/2026 LPB - 02/25/2026
1 (b) All out-of-state locations identified in the notice are located
2 within public buildings used by members of the entity or at a place which
3 will accommodate the anticipated audience;
4 (c) Reasonable arrangements are made to accommodate the public's
5 right to attend, hear, and speak at the meeting, including making virtual
6 conferencing available at an instate location to members, the public, or
7 the press, if requested twenty-four hours in advance;
8 (d) No more than twenty-five percent of the public body's meetings
9 in a calendar year are held out-of-state;
10 (e) Out-of-state meetings are not used to circumvent any of the
11 public government purposes established in the Open Meetings Act; and
12 (f) The public body publishes notice of the out-of-state meeting at
13 least twenty-one days before the date of the meeting in a legal newspaper
14 of statewide circulation.
15 (7) Each public body shall, upon request, make a reasonable effort
16 to accommodate the public's right to hear the discussion and testimony
17 presented at a meeting.
18 (8) Public bodies shall make available at the meeting or the instate
19 location for virtual conferencing as required by subdivision (6)(c) of
20 this section, for examination and copying by members of the public, at
21 least one copy of all reproducible written material to be discussed at an
22 open meeting, either in paper or electronic form. Public bodies shall
23 make available at least one current copy of the Open Meetings Act posted
24 in the meeting room at a location accessible to members of the public. At
25 the beginning of the meeting, the public shall be informed about the
26 location of the posted information.
